  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Task Force Impact Investment</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">As part of its programmes, Solidaridad builds compelling business cases to generate investment opportunities, mobilizing a blend of grants, equity and credits to obtain the financing needed to increase speed and scale and achieve long-term economic, environmental and social impacts.

This task force is a network-wide group of experts in the field of impact investment, and is responsible for support with regards to the development of bankable business models and the engagement of impact investors.  

In 2020, we invested strongly in the network wide capacity of the regional specialists on impact investment and access to finance. This resulted in the development of new proposals and initiatives to increase farmers&#x2019; access to finance. Examples are the development of credit scoring and micro-finance in West Africa, a loan-management platform for crop maintenance in Colombia and climate-funding proposals in India and Indonesia.
We systematized and analysed several impact investment projects and opportunities and drew important lessons for our future strategic direction: among the main valuable lessons is the need to shift away from the large ticket sizes (&gt; 500,000 euros) towards smaller investment needs for SMEs, the so-called &#x201C;missing middle&#x201D;. Increased attention for the development of financial instruments for smallholders became evident.
To target the &#x201C;missing middle&#x201D;, we launched the PlusPlus platform in partnership with Lendahand, Cordaid and Truvalu, in 2020. In total, the platform disbursed 9 loans to 6 counterparts with a total amount of 160,000 euros. Funding has been secured to build the coming years a pipeline with suitable candidates for funding in the Central American, East African and South African regions. In 2020, the GOWN Platform that targets specifically women-led SMEs, was designed and pre-tested among 5 SMEs, in 2021 the platform will be validated among 50 SMEs.</narrative>
  </description>
